Why use unsafe rust?
1. Static analysis is conservative by nature. Rust will reject a program if it is not guarenteed to be memory safe, even though the devs know it is memory safe.
2. Underlying computer hardware is inherently unsafe. System's programming language should allow to write unsafe code when required.

Unsafe rust uses the keyword -> 'unsafe' which allows:
1. Dereference a raw pointer
2. Call an unsafe function / method
3. Access or modify a mutable static variable.
4. Implement an unsafe trait.
5. Access fields of Union.

Keep unsafe code isolated and small so that it is easy to debug.


Unsafe rust has 2 types of raw pointers:
1. mutable raw pointers
2. immutable raw pointers